> Dear Saravanan and Sasi,
>
> I have reviewed the v6 document and both sets of feedback. Let me 
> address each point directly.
>
> *On the three CEO-directed corrections*
>
> Sasi, all three corrections directed in the v5 review mail have been 
> applied correctly. W1 — CD-7 is marked RESOLVED with the full 
> confirmation note. W2 — the E36 typo is correctly numbered as CD-8 and 
> the Scorecard is updated consistently. W3 — the Division Setup UI 
> approval configuration recommendation has been added to Section 12.3 
> with the right content. *These are done well and I acknowledge the work.*
>
> *On PM Saravanan's three issues
> *
> Saravanan, I have verified all three points against the document. *You 
> are correct on all three. Let me explain why.*
>
> Issue 1 — FastReports vs QuestPDF conflict
>
> Saravanan is right. This is the most important of the three.
>
> Sasi, I have checked every section of the document. The QuestPDF 
> decision is correctly stated in Section 12.4, which reads: 
> 'Transaction PDF prints use QuestPDF (MIT-licensed C# library) — not 
> Crystal Reports, not FastReports.' That section is right. But the 
> following sections still say FastReports:
>
> Section 5.11 Step 5: 'The FastReports template must include a 
> visibility expression on these fields.'
> Section 7.2: 'FastReports migration proceeds from the generalised JAT 
> template.' And in the SPINRISE replacement row: 'implement 
> IReportService using FastReport.Net or SSRS.'
> Section 13 IST-3 answer: 'FastReports template must include a 
> visibility condition on these two fields.'
> Section 13 IST-9 answer: 'FastReports migration: single template 
> RPT_RMI_PO.'
> Section 14 Scorecard, Report Architecture row: 'FastReports migration: 
> single RPT_RMI_PO template.'
>
> That is five places saying FastReports and one place saying QuestPDF. 
> A developer reading this document cannot know which to implement.
>
> Your reply to PM Saravanan — 'The report tool has not yet been 
> finalized. It will be updated at a later stage once the decision is 
> confirmed' —*is factually incorrect.* The QuestPDF decision was 
> confirmed by me in the v5 review mail, confirmed again in the VB FSD 
> Claude Guide v3 published on 12 April, and your own Section 12.4 
> records it as a decided CEO technology decision. The decision is 
> confirmed. Section 12.4 is correct. The other five sections must match it.
>
> *The fix is straightforward: *in every place where FastReports appears 
> in Sections 5.11, 7.2, 13, and 14, replace it with QuestPDF. The 
> SPINRISE template name changes from RPT_RMI_PO.frp (FastReports 
> format) to a QuestPDF C# class. The visibility condition logic in 
> Section 5.11 Step 5 remains the same — only the technology reference 
> changes.
>
>
> *Issue 2 — SuppLotNoReqArrival default inconsistency*
>
> Saravanan is right on this one too.
>
> Sasi, your reply says 'Decided to set default value as Y. Clearly 
> specified at document level.' But the document says N in Section 11 
> and Y in Section 4. A document cannot be its own contradiction. 
> Section 11 is the single source of truth for SPINRISE defaults — it is 
> the table that a new-customer onboarding engineer will reference when 
> configuring SPINRISE. If Section 11 says N and the correct default is 
> Y, we will have misconfigured installations.
>
> The fix: change Section 11 SuppLotNoReqArrival default from N to Y. 
> Then add a note in the same row: 'Existing Kalsofte VB6 customers 
> currently configured with N must be explicitly updated at SPINRISE 
> onboarding.' This preserves both the correct SPINRISE default and the 
> migration note for existing sites. Section 4 and Section 11 will then 
> be consistent.
>
>
> *Issue 3 — Cover page version label*
>
> Saravanan is right on this too.
>
> Sasi, I understand your reasoning. The 'FSD v3 Template' label refers 
> to the VB FSD Claude Guide template version. But a developer reading 
> this document for the first time sees 'FSD v3 Template — 14 Sections' 
> on the cover and 'Approved Version: v6' in the Document Identity 
> table, and will wonder whether v3 and v6 refer to the same version or 
> different things. That confusion is real and must be removed.
>
> The guide version does not belong on the cover page of the FSD. The 
> cover page is the face of the document — it should identify the 
> document, not the methodology framework. The fix: change 'FSD v3 
> Template — 14 Sections' to 'FSD v6 — 14 Sections'. The guide framework 
> version can be noted in a document properties field or not at all.
>
>
> *Summary of what Sasi must correct in v7*
>
> All three are text replacements. None require new analysis. Estimated 
> time: 20 minutes.
>
> *Correction 1: *Replace all FastReports references with QuestPDF in 
> Sections 5.11, 7.2, 13 (IST-3 and IST-9 answers), and Section 14 
> Scorecard. Section 12.4 is already correct — leave it as-is and make 
> the other five locations match it.
>
> *Correction 2: *Section 11 SuppLotNoReqArrival default: change N to Y. 
> Add the migration note for existing customers.
>
> *Correction 3: *Cover page: change 'FSD v3 Template — 14 Sections' to 
> 'FSD v6 — 14 Sections'.
>
> Once done, submit v7 directly to TL-IST Palanivel for TL-IST sign-off, 
> with cc to PM Saravanan. Palanivel's TL-IST sign-off is the next step 
> in the review chain before PM Stage 4 and CEO approval.
>
> *Sasi, the core FSD work is excellent. We are three text corrections 
> away from approval. Do not delay on this.
> *
> Regards,
> T. Mani
>
> cc: TL-IST Palanivel (next: TL-IST sign-off on v7 when received)
